1-
Git is distributed version control system, free and open scorce 
github simplify using git .
you can use git without github.
github is source for project and sources.
git has GUI  

2-
git fetch:downloads commits, files, and refs (references like branch pointers) from a remote repository to your local repository
git pull:This command is a combination of git fetch followed by git merge.
It first fetches the latest changes from the remote repository and then automatically merges those changes into your current local branch.
This directly updates your working directory with the remote changes.


3-
The .gitignore file serves to inform Git about which files and directories within a repository should be intentionally excluded from version control. 
This prevents these specified items from being tracked, staged, or committed to the repository.
a)Excluding temporary or generated files 
b)Preventing sensitive data exposure
c)Maintaining a clean repository
d)Improving performance


4-
Fork the Repository: creates a personal copy of the repository under your GitHub account, allowing you to make changes without affecting the original project directly.
Clone Your Fork: Clone your forked repository to your local machine using Git.
Create a New Branch: Create a new branch for your specific contribution to keep your changes isolated and organized.
Make Your Changes: Implement the desired features, bug fixes, or improvements within your local branch.
Commit Your Changes: Stage and commit your changes with clear and concise commit messages
Push Your Branch: Push your new branch and its commits to your forked repository on GitHub.
Open a Pull Request:On GitHub, navigate to your forked repository and open a pull request. This initiates a request to merge your changes from your branch into the original project's main branch. Provide a detailed description of your contribution in the pull request.
Address Feedback and Collaborate:Project maintainers may review your pull request and provide feedback or request modifications. Respond to comments, make necessary adjustments, and push updated commits to your branch.
Merge or Close: Once your changes are approved, the maintainers will merge your pull request into the main project. If your contribution is not accepted, the pull request may be closed.
